    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nRemote-ssh feature currently hardcodes `/tmp/nvim-remote.sock` as the Unix domain socket path on the remote host. If multiple users or multiple sessions from the same user connect to the same machine, they will collide on the same socket path - the second connection will either fail or hijack the first session.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nGenerate unique socket paths per session, for example by incorporating the local user, PID, or a random token into the socket name (e.g. `/tmp/nvim-remote-{user}-{token}.sock`). The forwarding (-L) and teardown logic need to track the per-session path. \n\nRef: #39378",
    "closed_at": null,
